Is this true: Every ideal of $K[x_1,\ldots,x_n]$ is generated by some subset with $\leq n$ elements? It is true when $n=1$, since $K[x]$ is a PID. I'm trying to prove it is not true for $n\geq2$, via the example $I:=\langle x^2,xy,y^2\rangle\unlhd K[x,y]$. Does the SINGULAR code below confirm that $I$ is not generated by $1$ or $2$ polynomials? ring R=0,(x,y),ls;
ideal I=x2,xy,y2;
minbase(I); From the SINGULAR manual: 5.1.76 minbase Syntax: minbase ( ideal_expression )  minbase ( module_expression ) Type: the same as the type of the argument Purpose: returns a minimal set of generators of an ideal, resp. module, if the input is either homogeneous or if the ordering is local . What does a "minimal set of generators" mean? Minimal w.r.t. cardinality, or w.r.t. $\subseteq$?
